ims and Christians in Antakya, Turkey -- tAestheticisation and the Production of (Religious) Space in Chennai -- tMoving Religion by Sound: On the Effectiveness of the Nāda-Brahman in India and Modern Europe -- tPART IV. Concepts and Theories -- tEsoteric Aesthetics: The Spiritual Matter of Intersubjective Encounter -- tAesthetics of Immersion: Collective Effervescence, Bodily Synchronisation and the Sensory Navigation of the Sacred -- tThe Governance of Aesthetic Subjects Through Body Knowledge and Affect Economies. A Cognitive-Aesthetic Approach -- tReligion in the Flesh: Non-Reductive Materialism and the Ecological Aesthetics of Religion -- tPART V. In Conversation: Essays About the Connectivity of an Aesthetics of Religion -- tSubjects and Sense-Making -- tConsumer Culture and the Sensory Remodelling of Religion -- tSocial Aesthetics, Atmosphere and Proprioception -- tSemiotics and Aesthetics: Historical and Structural Connections -- tThe Artificiality of Aesthetics: Making Connections on the Erie Canal -- tAuthors Biographies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume is the first English language presentation of the innovative approaches developed in the aesthetics of religion. The chapters present diverse material and detailed analysis on descriptive, methodological and theoretical concepts that together explore the potential of an aesthetic approach for investigating religion as a sensory and mediated practice. In dialogue with, yet different from, other major movements in the field (material culture, anthropology of the senses, for instance), it is the specific intent of this approach to create a framework for understanding the interplay between sensory, cognitive and socio-cultural aspects of world-construction. The volume demonstrates that aesthetics, as a theory of sensory knowledge, offers an elaborate repertoire of concepts that can help to understand religious traditions. These approaches take into account contemporary developments in scientific theories of perception, neuro-aesthetics and cultural studies, highlighting the socio-cultural and political context informing how humans perceive themselves and the world around them. Developing since the 1990s, the aesthetic approach has responded to debates in the study of religion, in particular striving to overcome biased categories that confined religion either to texts and abstract beliefs, or to an indisputable sui generis mode of experience. This volume documents what has been achieved to date, its significance for the study of religion and for interdisciplinary scholarship.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aReligionstheorie. 4aSinne. 4aWahrnehmung. 4aÄsthetik. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aPerception.  aSenses.  aTheory of Religion.1 aAktor, Mikael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuffarth, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunotte, Ulrike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummins, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldt, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGauthier, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrieser, Alexandra K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrieser, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, John T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeidemann, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHermann, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab